{"title_page": "National Association of Secretaries of State", "text_new": "{{infobox organization \n| name = National Association of Secretaries of State\n| abbreviation = NASS\n| founded = {{start date and age|1904}}\n| logo = NASSorglogo.png\n| tax_id = 61-1332655<ref name= irseos>\"[https://apps.irs.gov/app/eos/displayAll.do?dispatchMethod=displayAllInfo&Id=732104&ein=611332655&country=US&deductibility=all&dispatchMethod=searchAll&isDescending=false&city=&ein1=&postDateFrom=&exemptTypeCode=al&submitName=&sortColumn=orgName&totalResults=1&names=National+Association+of+Secretaries+of+State&resultsPerPage=25&indexOfFirstRow=0&postDateTo=&state=All+States National Association of Secretaries of State Inc.]\" ''Tax Exempt Organization Search''. [[Internal Revenue Service]]. Retrieved March 5, 2020.</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coords|38.895777|-77.009186|display=inline,title}}\n| headquarters = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| status = [[Professional association|Professional]] [[nonprofit organization]]\n| type = [[501(c)(3)]]<ref name= irseos/> \n| revenue = $1,107,581<ref name= 990-2017>\"[https://apps.irs.gov/pub/epostcard/cor/611332655_201806_990_2019110416813668.pdf Form 990: Return of Organization Exempt from Income Tax]\". ''National Association of Secretaries of State''. [[Internal Revenue Service]]. June 30, 2018.</ref>\n| revenue_year = 2018\n| expenses = $992,261<ref name= 990-2017/>\n| expenses_year = 2018\n| employees = 6<ref name= 990-2017/>\n| employees_year = 2017\n| leader_name = Leslie Reynolds<ref name= 990-2017/>\n| leader_title = [[Executive director]]\n| leader_name2 = [[Paul Pate]]<ref name= aboutnass>\"[https://www.nass.org/about-nass About NASS]\". ''National Association of Secretaries of State''. Retrieved March 5, 2020.</ref> \n| leader_title2 = [[President (corporation)|President]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.nass.org}}\n}}\nThe '''National Association of Secretaries of State''' ('''NASS'''), founded in 1904, is the oldest non-partisan professional organization of public officials in the United States,  composed of the [[Secretary of State (U.S. state government)|Secretaries of State]] of [[U.S. state]]s and [[territories of the United States|territories]]. Currently, all secretaries of state, including [[Washington D.C.]], [[Puerto Rico]], the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]], and [[Guam]]) are members of NASS.\n\nNASS maintains its office in [[Washington, D.C.]], and promotes positions on issues of interest to Secretaries of State: voter turnout, voting procedures, business services, electronic government, securities, and government archives.\n\n[[Pennsylvania Secretary of the Commonwealth]] [[Pedro A. Cort\u00e9s]] became the first Puerto Rican president of the organization, and the last one to hold the position for a full one-year term, followed by [[Maine Secretary of State]] [[Matthew Dunlap]], whose term was cut short by his electoral defeat in the 2010 midterm elections.  [[Minnesota Secretary of State]] [[Mark Ritchie]] filled the remainder of Dunlap's term.  During the organization's annual summer meeting in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] in July 2012, [[Alabama Secretary of State]] [[Beth Chapman]] turned over the presidency to [[Nevada Secretary of State]] [[Ross Miller]].\n\n==Positions of NASS==\nNASS has taken a stand on the issue of the [[United States presidential primaries]], promoting the [[Rotating Regional Primary System]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20070622000613/http://nass.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=74&Itemid=210 NASS Rotating Regional Presidential Primaries Plan]\". ''National Association of Secretaries of State''. 2007. Archived from [http://nass.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=74&Itemid=210 the original] on June 22, 2007.</ref>\n\nNASS has called on the [[National Institute for Standards and Technology]] and the U.S. [[Election Assistance Commission]] to publish a plain English guide to the new [[Voluntary Voting System Guidelines]]. (July 2007) [http://nass.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=28&Itemid=159]\n\nNASS has also published a position paper on Federal legislation, calling on the Congress to respect states rights. (February 2007) [http://nass.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=28&Itemid=159]\n\n==NASS Presidents==\n* [[Paul Pate]], [[Iowa]] (2019\u20132020)<ref name= aboutnass/> \n* [[Jim Condos]], [[Vermont]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name= pastpres>\"[https://www.nass.org/sites/default/files/nass-history/5-Presidents-19.pdf Past Presidents]\". ''National Association of Secretaries of State''. Retrieved March 5, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Connie Lawson]], [[Indiana]] (2017\u20132018)<ref name= pastpres/>\n* [[Denise Merrill]], [[Connecticut]] (2016\u20132017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/sots/cwp/view.asp?a=3176&q=469626|title=SOTS: The Biography of Denise Merrill|website=www.ct.gov|language=en-us|access-date=June 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n* [[Elaine Marshall]], [[North Carolina]] (2015)<ref name=\":0\">\"[http://www.nass.org/index.php/news-releases-and-statements/news-release-president-marshall-feb15/ National Association of Secretaries of State Announces New President]\". ''National Association of Secretaries of State''. Retrieved June 6, 2017.</ref>\n* [[Kate Brown]], [[Oregon]] (2014\u2013February 2015)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Tre Hargett]], [[Tennessee]] (2013\u20132014)\n* [[Ross Miller]], [[Nevada]] (2012\u20132013)\n* [[Beth Chapman]], [[Alabama]] (2011\u20132012)\n* [[Mark Ritchie]], [[Minnesota]] (2011)<ref>[http://www.nass.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=247:news-release-ritchie-new-prez-2011&catid=29]</ref>\n* [[Matthew Dunlap]], [[Maine]] (2010\u2013January 2011)\n* [[Trey Grayson]], [[Kentucky]] (2009\u20132010)\n* [[Pedro Cort\u00e9s]], [[Pennsylvania]] (2008\u20132009)\n* [[Todd Rokita]], [[Indiana]] (2007\u20132008)\n* [[Deb Markowitz]], [[Vermont]] (2006\u20132007)\n* [[Sam Reed]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] (August 2005\u20132006)\n* [[Donetta Davidson]], [[Colorado]] (July 2005\u2013August 2005)\n* [[Rebecca Vigil-Giron]], [[New Mexico]] (2004\u20132005)\n* [[Mary Kiffmeyer]], [[Minnesota]] (2003\u20132004)\n* [[Dan Gwadosky]], [[Maine]] (2002\u20132003)\n* [[Ron Thornburgh]], [[Kansas]] (2001\u20132002)\n* [[Sharon Priest]], [[Arkansas]] (2000\u20132001)\n* [[James R. Bennett|Jim Bennett]], [[Alabama]] (1999\u20132000)\n* [[Bill Gardner (politician)|Bill Gardner]], [[New Hampshire]] (1998\u20131999)\n* [[Olene Walker]], [[Utah]] (1997\u20131998)\n* [[Mike Cooney]], [[Montana]] (1996\u20131997)\n* [[Joyce Hazeltine]], [[South Dakota]] (1995\u20131996)\n* [[Rufus Edminston]], [[North Carolina]] (1994\u20131995)\n* [[Natalie Meyer]], [[Colorado]] (1993\u20131994)\n* [[Gail Shafer]], [[New York (state)|New York]] (1992\u20131993)\n* [[Dick Molpus]], [[Mississippi]] (1991\u20131992)\n* [[Ralph Munro]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] (1990\u20131991)\n* [[Julia Tashjian]], [[Connecticut]] (1989\u20131990)\n* [[Jim Edgar]], [[Illinois]] (1988\u20131989)\n* [[Jim Waltermire]], [[Montana]] (1987){{efn|name=dio}}\n* [[James H. Douglas]], [[Vermont]] (1986\u20131987)\n* [[Jeanette B. Edmonston]], [[Oklahoma]] (1985\u20131986)\n* [[Edwin J. Simcox]], [[Indiana]] (1984\u20131985)\n* [[Jack H. Brier]], [[Kansas]] (1983\u20131984)\n* [[Rose Mofford]], [[Arizona]] (1982\u20131983)\n* [[Robert Burns]], [[Rhode Island]] (1981\u20131982)\n* [[Gentry Crowell]], [[Tennessee]] (1980\u20131981)\n* [[Joan Anderson Crowe]], [[Minnesota]] (1979\u20131980)\n* [[Alan J. Dixon]], [[Illinois]] (1978\u20131979)\n* [[Fred L. Wineland]], [[Maryland]] (1977\u20131978)\n* [[Mark White]], [[Texas]] (1977)\n* [[Allen J. Beermann]], [[Nebraska]] (1976\u20131977)\n* [[Elwill M. Shanahan]], [[Kansas]] (1975\u20131976)\n* [[Clyde L. Miller]], [[Utah]] (1974\u20131975)\n* [[James C. Kirkpatrick]], [[Missouri]] (1973\u20131974)\n* [[Byron A. Anderson]], [[Colorado]] (1972\u20131973)\n* [[Kelly Bryant]], [[Arkansas]] (1971\u2013